Function: The party approaches Forelhost and discovers that the exterior is an ancient battlefield where the Nordic siege army died trying to get in. Environmental storytelling establishes the tomb's history and the Dragon Cult's fanaticism. A guardian encounter tests the party before entry.
Location: A mountain peak south of Riften. The path climbs through autumn forest into thin, cold air. Forelhost sits at the summit — a massive Nordic stone fortification built into the mountainside, half-buried in snow.
THE ROOM (Read Aloud)
"The path crests the ridgeline and you see it: Forelhost, the Last Redoubt. A fortress of black stone fused into the mountain itself, its walls angled like a jaw clenched shut. Snow has buried the lower battlements. The main gate — a pair of iron-banded doors twenty feet tall — stands open. Not broken. Open. As if someone walked out and never closed them behind them.
The ground between the treeline and the gate is wrong. The snow here is shallow — thin enough to see what's underneath. Bones. Hundreds of them. Ancient Nord skeletons in corroded armor, scattered across the approach in overlapping layers. Siege ladders lie rotted in the snow. Rusted swords and shattered shields carpet the frozen earth. This is where the Nordic army died — not inside the fortress, but outside it, failing to breach the walls.
Among the ancient dead, something moves. Three figures pace the snow between the bones — skeletal warriors in the remnants of Dragon Cult robes, eye sockets burning with cold blue light. They patrol a fixed pattern around the gate, stepping over the bones of the army that killed their congregation. They have been doing this for four thousand years."
Then improvise from: The wind is constant and cutting. Crows circle overhead. The fortress radiates cold — not weather cold, death cold. The bones underfoot crunch like frozen branches.
WHAT'S IN THIS ROOM
The ancient battlefield: What they see: Hundreds of Nord skeletons in corroded armor. If they investigate (Magic TN 12): These soldiers died of poison, not combat. No blade wounds on the bones. The siege army was poisoned — likely by contaminated water or biological warfare from inside the fortress. The Dragon Cult didn't just kill themselves. They weaponized their own death, poisoning the besieging army as a final act. Why planted here: Establishes Forelhost's history as a bioweapons site from the very beginning. Antoine didn't CREATE the lab — he inherited a tradition.
The open gate: What they see: The doors are open. Not forced — opened from inside. If they investigate: Recently. Within the last few months. The hinges have been oiled. Someone has been coming and going. Antoine's entry point. Why planted here: Confirms the tomb is actively in use.
The skeletal patrols (×3): What they see: Three undead Dragon Cult guardians. If they investigate: They don't leave the killing field. They patrol a set perimeter. They will attack anything that enters their patrol zone. Why planted here: The Section 1 guardian encounter.
