SECTION 5: THE LABORATORY
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
Function: The reward room. Antoine's inner sanctum and active laboratory. Contains his most advanced research, the Tears of Rahgot growing in their only natural habitat, actionable intelligence for Maven's bounty, and rare alchemical reagents. Also contains Rahgot's sarcophagus — open, empty, ward-runes dark. The Dragon Priest who slept here for four thousand years is awake and walking. This is the party's first proof that the Dragon Priests are not just historical threats — they are active, present, and pursuing an agenda.
Location: The inner sanctum of Forelhost. A circular chamber of polished black stone. The air is cold and perfectly still — or was, before the party opened the door.
THE ROOM (Read Aloud)
"The inner sanctum is a circle of black stone, forty feet across, lit by enchanted braziers that cast steady white light — no flickering, no shadows. Clinical. The floor is seamless and clean. The air is cold and tastes of nothing — absolutely nothing. No dust, no moisture, no organic trace. This is what perfect sterility feels like.
Workstations ring the outer wall — glass apparatus more advanced than anything in the outer alcoves, sealed culture dishes arranged in precise grids, instruments you cannot name. At the center of the room, on a raised stone dais, sits a massive sarcophagus carved with Dragon Cult iconography. The lid has been pushed aside — shoved with tremendous force, cracked where it struck the dais edge. The interior is empty. Ward-runes line the inner surface, but they are dark. Dead. Whatever was sleeping here is not sleeping anymore.
The dust pattern inside the sarcophagus shows a clear impression — a large humanoid form, arms crossed, lying for millennia. And then rising.
Between the workstations and the sarcophagus, in a crescent of dark soil contained by a stone planter, something grows. Flowers. Small, deep crimson, with petals that seem to weep — beads of dark liquid gathering at the petal tips and dripping into the soil. The soil itself is dark and rich and wrong — it pulses faintly, as if alive. The flowers grow nowhere else. They cannot grow anywhere else.
On the central workstation, a leather-bound folder sits open. The handwriting is the same small, precise script from the journals. A note is pinned to the front page: 'Strain 2.0 — Design Parameters. FOR MY EYES ONLY.'"
Then improvise from: The silence. The white light. The empty sarcophagus gaping open like a mouth. The weeping flowers. The smell — or rather the absolute absence of smell. This is the cleanest, most controlled space any of them have ever entered. It is also the most dangerous. And whatever ancient horror used to sleep at its center is now loose in the world.
WHAT'S IN THIS ROOM
The Tears of Rahgot (the weeping flowers): What they see: Crimson flowers growing in dark, pulsing soil. If they investigate (Magic TN 12): These are the Tears of Rahgot — the extinct binding agent Alfonso identified through Peryite. They grow only in soil saturated with the blood and death-energy of Rahgot's congregation. The "tears" — the weeping liquid — is the concentrated floral toxin Antoine uses as his plague's binding agent. Harvesting them is straightforward but handling the extract requires alchemical skill (Magic TN 14 to safely collect 3 doses). Why planted here: Confirmation of Alfonso's investigation. Rare reagent. Also: beautiful and horrifying. Flowers watered by four thousand years of human death.
Rahgot's sarcophagus (OPEN): What they see: A massive stone sarcophagus, lid shoved aside, interior empty. Ward-runes dark. A body-impression in the dust. If they investigate (Magic TN 12): The ward-runes were a death-sleep preservation system — keeping the occupant in suspended animation for millennia. They were deactivated deliberately, from the inside. Whatever was in here woke up on its own and walked out. The dust impression shows a large humanoid form wearing a mask. The sarcophagus carvings identify the occupant: Rahgot, Dragon Priest of the Last Redoubt.
If they investigate further (Magic TN 14 or Alfonso automatic): The carvings around the sarcophagus tell a story. Dragon Priests were the mortal servants of the dragons during the Merethic Era — men and women who ruled over human kingdoms as intermediaries between the dragon gods and their mortal subjects. They were granted immense power and near-immortality in exchange for absolute devotion. When the ancient Nords overthrew the Dragon Cult in the Dragon War, most priests were killed or sealed in their tombs in death-sleep.
The carvings name FIVE priests who entered death-sleep rather than face destruction. Each has a title and a mask:
Nahkriin the Guardian — mask of vengeance. Spymaster. Guards the path to Sovngarde.
Vokun the Shadow — mask of shadow. Tactician and siege commander.
Rahgot the Angry — mask of fury. Alchemist-priest. Weapon of environmental destruction. This sarcophagus.
Otar the Mad — mask of madness. A king who believes his kingdom never fell.
Morokei the Glorious — mask of glory. Archmage. The most powerful of the five.
The carvings depict a final image: all five masks placed together on a single altar, forming a sixth mask — Konahrik, the Warlord. The inscription beneath reads: "When the World-Eater returns, the faithful shall rise. When the five become one, the faithful shall ascend."
What this means: The Dragon Priests aren't just waking up to serve Alduin. They have their own agenda. The five masks combine into something greater. "Ascend" implies apotheosis — they intend to become gods. Alduin is their vehicle, not their master.
Alfonso's read (automatic): "Rahgot was an alchemist-priest. Environmental warfare was his doctrine four thousand years ago. Antoine isn't his apprentice — he's his successor. Rahgot woke up, found a prodigy already working in his laboratory, and put him to work. The plagues aren't Antoine's project. They're Rahgot's. Antoine is the instrument. Rahgot is the hand."
Why planted here: The empty sarcophagus is the session's biggest revelation. Dragon Priests are awake, active, organized, and pursuing apotheosis. Rahgot specifically is loose in the world with an alchemist-servant and a grudge against the descendants who besieged his fortress. This connects directly to the Dragon Cult clock's Tier 3 event (Rahgot's ecological assault on the Rift).
The Strain 2.0 design folder: What they see: Antoine's active research on the next-generation pathogen. If they investigate: See detailed breakdown below. Why planted here: The primary intelligence reward and the party's ticking clock.
The culture dishes: What they see: Sealed glass dishes arranged in grids. If they investigate: Active pathogen cultures in various stages. This is where the infection risk lives. If containment was breached (Outcomes B or C), these are now open to the air. If containment held (Outcome A), they're still sealed and safe to study. Why planted here: The source of the infection and also a potential loot item — sealed culture samples are worth 500g each to Maven (proof of the operation) or to Alfonso (research material).
STRAIN 2.0 DESIGN FOLDER
Antoine's magnum opus in progress. Alfonso can read this without a roll — it's his discipline. Other PCs need Magic TN 16.
Key contents:
Design Goals: "Strain 2.0 must achieve what 1.0 could not: self-propagation beyond the initial vector. 1.0 was a field test — single-vector, non-replicating. 2.0 will be waterborne, airborne, AND transmissible through Restoration magic. A healer who cures one patient becomes the vector for the next hundred."
The Missing Ingredient: "The divine frequency remains the final barrier. My engineering can achieve mechanical perfection but cannot replicate the self-sustaining lifecycle of a true plague. The Peryite carrier's infection — to be extracted from Subject Ulag upon my arrival at his position — may provide the solution. If the divine frequency can be grafted onto the Strain 2.0 chassis, the result will be both engineered and organic. Immortal. Self-correcting. Perfect."
"Estimated time to completion once extraction yields viable samples: six to eight weeks."
